						               													<description>Tactical level wargame based on the Japanese animated series &amp;quot;Armored Trooper Votoms&amp;quot;. The game was developed over five different games published in Dual Magazine issues no. 6 to no. 10. Each game featured a different setting but used same basic rules with different map and units. Game no. 5, &amp;quot;Armored Trooper,&amp;quot; serves as an omnibus edition and collects most of the rules from the previous four games.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Players each control one or more piloted Armored Trooper mecha units (AT for short).&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Each turn, players choose a behavior, called an &amp;quot;Action Pattern&amp;quot; for each unit. An action pattern (such as Run, Walk, Fire (Weapon), Dive (Underwater), and Roller Dash (use roller skate-like wheels)) determines how a unit may move and how well it performs in combat for that turn. Players also plot their movement and how many shots they will fire from a ranged weapon, if any.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;All movement takes place simultaneously and the players move their units on a hex map.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;After movement, ranged and close combat (called &amp;quot;Battling&amp;quot;) are resolved. All action is simultaneous, so results of damage do not take effect until the end of the turn.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;In the basic game, each player use one Armored Trooper and battle to destroy the opponent. A skilled player can handle more Armored Troopers for large-scale battles. A few scenarios are included, but players are expected to design their own combat situations.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Game no. 3 &amp;quot;Outer Space Battle&amp;quot; is very different from the other games. It uses vector-based movement in outer space and only a small number of AT units are able to be used outside of the atmosphere.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
